        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1896729984" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13024445935832076506">Never Let You Go is a very good title for this book. It&apos;s positive, but also menacing, depending on the context. This is a story with many layers. The author really put some work into her narrative. If the stalker were to be removed from the book, it would still be a potential page turner.<br/><br/>Initially, I had to drag myself to read this one. Unlike regular Goodreads friends, I&apos;m not weathered by the violence and budding threats that are so often in thriller books. These aren&apos;t spy books. They are th</span>
  <span id="freeText13024445935832076506" style="display:none">Never Let You Go is a very good title for this book. It's positive, but also menacing, depending on the context. This is a story with many layers. The author really put some work into her narrative. If the stalker were to be removed from the book, it would still be a potential page turner.<br /><br />Initially, I had to drag myself to read this one. Unlike regular Goodreads friends, I'm not weathered by the violence and budding threats that are so often in thriller books. These aren't spy books. They are thrillers, and I have to say, this one is a hell of a thriller.<br /><br />The novel revolves around Lindsey Nash, her husband Andrew, and their daughter Sophie. Andrew got sent to jail for vehicular manslaughter, and Lindsey escapes from her life of abuse. Fast forward to Now and Lindsey is very close to her teenage daughter, but someone wants to upset that particular apple cart. I even found the constant back and forth between now and then, refreshing. I loved this book, and I hope it shows in my review.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13024445935832076506" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
